{"id":"astro-ph/0101231","submitter":"David Maurin","authors":"D.Maurin (LAPTH Annecy, Universite de Savoie), F.Donato (LAPTH\n  Annecy), R.Taillet (LAPTH Annecy, Universite de Savoie), P.Salati (LAPTH\n  Annecy, Universite de Savoie)","title":"Cosmic Rays below Z=30 in a diffusion model: new constraints on\n  propagation parameters","comments":"19 pages, 8 figures, submitted to ApJ, revised version","journal-ref":"Astrophys.J.555:585-596,2001","doi":"10.1086/321496","report-no":"preprint LAPTH 817/00","categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Cosmic ray nuclei fluxes are expected to be measured with high precision in\nthe near future. For instance, high quality data on the antiproton component\ncould give important clues about the nature of the astronomical dark matter. A\nvery good understanding of the different aspects of cosmic ray propagation is\ntherefore necessary. In this paper, we use cosmic ray nuclei data to give\nconstraints on the diffusion parameters. Propagation is studied with\nsemi-analytical solutions of a diffusion model, and we give new analytical\nsolutions for radioactively produced species. Our model includes convection and\nreacceleration as well as the standard energy losses. We perform a $\\chi^2$\nanalysis over B/C data for a large number of configurations obtained by varying\nthe relevant parameters of the diffusion model. A very good agreement with B/C\ndata arises for a number of configurations, all of which are compatible with\nsub-Fe/Fe data. Different source spectra $Q(E)$ and diffusion coefficients\n$K(E)$ have been tried, but for both parameters only one form gives a good fit.\nAnother important result is that models without convection or without\nreacceleration are excluded. We find that the various parameters, i.e. the\ndiffusion coefficient normalisation $K_0$ and spectral index $\\delta$, the halo\nthickness $L$, the Alfv\\'en velocity $V_a$, and the convection velocity $V_c$\nare strongly correlated. We obtain limits on the spectral index $\\delta$ of\nthediffusion coefficient, and in particular we exclude a Kolmogorov spectrum\n($\\delta = 1/3$).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 15 Jan 2001 10:32:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 3 Mar 2001 12:06:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-11-26"}
